# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bcpl-b-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] B was designed for recursive, non-numeric, machine-independent applications, such as system and language software.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] It was a typeless language, with the only data type being the underlying machine's natural memory word format, whatever that might be.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Depending on the context, the word was treated either as an integer or a memory address.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] As machines with ASCII processing became common, notably the DEC PDP-11 that arrived at Bell Labs, support for character data stuffed in memory words became important.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] The typeless nature of the language was seen as a disadvantage, which led Thompson and Ritchie to develop an expanded version of the language supporting new internal and user-defined types, which became the ubiquitous C programming language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Ken Thompson began developing B as a Fortran compiler for the PDP-7, but found that his initial implementation far exceeded available memory.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Through several iterations of simplifying the compiler and adapting the language to his own tastes that were influenced by BCPL, he arrived at a language that expressed a subset of BCPL semantics in a distinct syntax.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Thompson named the language B, which has been variously explained as an abbreviation of BCPL or Bon, another language he had developed, although he confirmed neither explanation.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Thompson added "two-address assignment operators" using `x =+ y` syntax to add y to x (in C the operator is written `+=`).
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] This syntax came from Douglas McIlroy's implementation of TMG, in which B's compiler was first implemented (and it came to TMG from ALGOL 68's `x +:= y` syntax).
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Thompson went further by inventing the increment and decrement operators (`++` and `--`).
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Their prefix or postfix position determines whether the value is taken before or after alteration of the operand.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] This innovation was not in the earliest versions of B.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] According to Dennis Ritchie, people often assumed that they were created for the auto-increment and auto-decrement address modes of the DEC PDP-11, but this is historically impossible as the machine didn't exist when B was first developed.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] B is typeless, or more precisely has one data type: the computer word.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`) treated this as an integer, but others treated it as a memory address to be dereferenced.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] In many other ways it looked a lot like an early version of C.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] It included a generalized for loop as later appeared in C, which Thompson adapted from earlier work by Stephen Johnson.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] There are a few library functions, including some that vaguely resemble functions from the standard I/O library in C.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] In Thompson's words: "B and the old old C were very very similar languages except for all the types [in C]".
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Early implementations were for the DEC PDP-7 and PDP-11 minicomputers using early Unix, and Honeywell GE 645 36-bit mainframes running the operating system GCOS.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] The earliest PDP-7 implementations compiled to threaded code, and Ritchie wrote a compiler using TMG which produced machine code.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] In 1970 a PDP-11 was acquired and threaded code was used for the port; an assembler, dc, and the B language itself were written in B to bootstrap the computer.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] An early version of yacc was produced with this PDP-11 configuration.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Ritchie took over maintenance during this period.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] The typeless nature of B made sense on the Honeywell, PDP-7 and many older computers, but was a problem on the PDP-11 because it was difficult to elegantly access the character data type that the PDP-11 and most modern computers fully support.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] Starting in 1971 Ritchie made changes to the language while converting its compiler to produce machine code, most notably adding data typing for variables.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] During 1971 and 1972 B evolved into "New B" (NB) and then C.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] B is almost extinct, having been superseded by the C language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] However, it continues to see use on GCOS mainframes (as of 2014) and on certain embedded systems (as of 2000) for a variety of reasons: limited hardware in small systems, extensive libraries, tooling, licensing cost issues, and simply being good enough for the job.
[src:bcpl-b-language/b-programming-language] The highly influential AberMUD was originally written in B.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was designed so that small and simple compilers could be written for it; reputedly some compilers could be run in 16 kilobytes.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Furthermore, the original compiler, itself written in BCPL, was easily portable.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was thus a popular choice for bootstrapping a system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] A major reason for the compiler's portability lay in its structure.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] It was split into two parts: the front end parsed the source and generated O-code, an intermediate language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The back end took the O-code and translated it into the machine code for the target machine.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Only 1⁄5 of the compiler's code needed to be rewritten to support a new machine, a task that usually took between 2 and 5 person-months.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] This approach became common practice later (e.g.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The language is unusual in having only one data type: a word, a fixed number of bits, usually chosen to align with the same platform architecture's machine word and of adequate capacity to represent any valid storage address.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] For many machines of the time, this data type was a 16-bit word.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] This choice later proved to be a significant problem when BCPL was used on machines in which the smallest addressable item was not a word but a byte or on machines with larger word sizes such as 32-bit or 64-bit.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The interpretation of any value was determined by the operators used to process the values.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] (For example, `+` added two values together, treating them as integers; `!` indirected through a value, effectively treating it as a pointer.) In order for this to work, the implementation provided no type checking.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The mismatch between BCPL's word orientation and byte-oriented hardware was addressed in several ways.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] One was by providing standard library routines for packing and unpacking words into byte strings.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Later, two language features were added: the bit-field selection operator and the infix byte indirection operator (denoted by `%`).
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL handles bindings spanning separate compilation units in a unique way.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] There are no user-declarable global variables; instead, there is a global vector, similar to "blank common" in Fortran.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] All data shared between different compilation units comprises scalars and pointers to vectors stored in a pre-arranged place in the global vector.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] As well as variables, the global vector contains bindings for external procedures.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] This makes dynamic loading of compilation units very simple to achieve.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Instead of relying on the link loader of the underlying implementation, effectively, BCPL gives the programmer control of the linking process.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The global vector also made it very simple to replace or augment standard library routines.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] A program could save the pointer from the global vector to the original routine and replace it with a pointer to an alternative version.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The alternative might call the original as part of its processing.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] This could be used as a quick *ad hoc* debugging aid.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was the first brace programming language and the braces survived the syntactical changes and have become a common means of denoting program source code statements.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] In practice, on limited keyboards of the day, source programs often used the sequences `$(` and `$)` or `[` and `]` in place of the symbols `{` and `}`.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The single-line `//` comments of BCPL, which were not adopted by C, reappeared in C++ and later in C99.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was first implemented by Martin Richards of the University of Cambridge in 1967.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was a response to difficulties with its predecessor, Cambridge Programming Language, later renamed Combined Programming Language (CPL), which was designed during the early 1960s.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Richards created BCPL by "removing those features of the full language which make compilation difficult".
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The first compiler implementation, for the IBM 7094 under Compatible Time-Sharing System, was written while Richards was visiting Project MAC at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in the spring of 1967.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The language was first described in a paper presented to the 1969 Spring Joint Computer Conference.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL has been rumored to have originally stood for "Bootstrap Cambridge Programming Language", but CPL was never created since development stopped at BCPL, and the acronym was later reinterpreted for the BCPL book.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL is the language in which the original "Hello, World!" program was written.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The first MUD was also written in BCPL (*MUD1*).
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Several operating systems were written partially or wholly in BCPL (for example, TRIPOS and the earliest versions of AmigaDOS).
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] BCPL was also the initial language used in the Xerox PARC Alto project.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Among other projects, the Bravo document preparation system was written in BCPL.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] An early compiler, bootstrapped in 1969, by starting with a paper tape of the O-code of Richards's Atlas 2 compiler, targeted the ICT 1900 series.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The two machines had different word-lengths (48 vs 24 bits), different character encodings, and different packed string representations—and the successful bootstrapping increased confidence in the practicality of the method.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] By late 1970, implementations existed for the Honeywell 635 and Honeywell 645, IBM 360, PDP-10, TX-2, CDC 6400, UNIVAC 1108, PDP-9, KDF 9 and Atlas 2.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] In 1974 a dialect of BCPL was implemented at BBN without using the intermediate O-code.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The initial implementation was a cross-compiler hosted on BBN's TENEX PDP-10s, and directly targeted the PDP-11s used in BBN's implementation of the second generation IMPs used in the ARPANET.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] There was also a version produced for the BBC Micro in the mid-1980s, by Richards Computer Products, a company started by John Richards, the brother of Martin Richards.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The BBC Domesday Project made use of the language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Versions of BCPL for the Amstrad CPC and Amstrad PCW computers were also released in 1986 by UK software house Arnor Ltd.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] MacBCPL was released for the Apple Macintosh in 1985 by Topexpress Ltd, of Kensington, England.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Both the design and philosophy of BCPL strongly influenced B, which in turn influenced C.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Programmers at the time debated whether an eventual successor to C would be called "D", the next letter in the alphabet, or "P", the next letter in the parent language name.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The language most accepted as being C's successor is C++ (with `++` being C's increment operator), although meanwhile, a D programming language also exists.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] In 1979, implementations of BCPL existed for at least 25 architectures; the language gradually fell out of favour as C became popular on non-Unix systems.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] Martin Richards maintains a modern version of BCPL on his website, last updated in 2023.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] This can be set up to run on various systems including Linux, FreeBSD, and Mac OS X.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] The latest distribution includes graphics and sound libraries, and there is a comprehensive manual.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] He continues to program in it, including for his research on musical automated score following.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] A common informal MIME type for BCPL is text/x-bcpl.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bcpl] If these programs are run using Richards' current version of Cintsys (December 2018), LIBHDR, START and WRITEF must be changed to lower case to avoid errors.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] In computer science, **bootstrapping** is the technique for producing a self-compiling compiler – that is, a compiler (or assembler) written in the source programming language that it intends to compile.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] An initial core version of the compiler (the *bootstrap compiler*) is generated in a different language (which could be assembly language); successive expanded versions of the compiler are developed using this minimal subset of the language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] The problem of compiling a self-compiling compiler has been called the chicken-or-egg problem in compiler design, and bootstrapping is a solution to this problem.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Bootstrapping is a fairly common practice when creating a programming language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Many compilers for many programming languages are bootstrapped, including compilers for ALGOL, BASIC, C, Common Lisp, D, Eiffel, Elixir, Factor, Go, Haskell, Java, Modula-2, Nim, Oberon, OCaml, Pascal, PL/I, Python, Rust, Scala, Scheme, TypeScript, Vala, Zig and more.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] The full compiler is built twice in order to compare the outputs of the two stages.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] If they are different, either the bootstrap or the full compiler contains a bug.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] If one needs to compile a compiler for language X written in language X, there is the issue of how the first compiler can be compiled.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Methods for distributing compilers in source code include providing a portable bytecode version of the compiler, so as to *bootstrap* the process of compiling the compiler with itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] The T-diagram is a notation used to explain these compiler bootstrap techniques.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] In some cases, the most convenient way to get a complicated compiler running on a system that has little or no software on it involves a series of ever more sophisticated assemblers and compilers.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Assemblers were the first language tools to bootstrap themselves.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] The first high-level language to provide such a bootstrap was NELIAC in 1958.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] The first widely used languages to do so were Burroughs B5000 Algol in 1961 and LISP in 1962.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Hart and Levin wrote a LISP compiler in LISP at MIT in 1962, testing it inside an existing LISP interpreter.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] Once they had improved the compiler to the point where it could compile its own source code, it was self-hosting.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] This technique is only possible when an interpreter already exists for the very same language that is to be compiled.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] It borrows directly from the notion of running a program on itself as input, which is also used in various proofs in theoretical computer science, such as the variation of the proof that the halting problem is undecidable that uses Rice's Theorem.
[src:bcpl-b-language/bootstrapping-compilers] These include the Bootstrappable builds project and the Reproducible builds project.
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] Richards studied mathematics as an undergraduate student at the University of Cambridge and took the Cambridge Diploma in Computer Science.
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] His PhD was on programming language design and implementation.
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] He was a senior lecturer at the University of Cambridge Computer Laboratory until his retirement in 2007.
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] In addition to BCPL, Richards' work includes the development of the TRIPOS portable operating system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] He was awarded the IEEE Computer Society's Computer Pioneer Award in 2003 for "pioneering system software portability through the programming language BCPL".
[src:bcpl-b-language/martin-richards-computer-scientist] Richards is a fellow of St John's College at the University of Cambridge.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Initial planning and development for Multics started in 1964, in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Originally it was a cooperative project led by MIT (Project MAC with Fernando Corbató) along with General Electric and Bell Labs.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] It was developed on the GE 645 computer, which was specially designed for it; the first one was delivered to MIT in January 1967.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] GE offered their earlier GE 635 systems with the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System, which they called "Mark I" and intended to offer the 645 with Multics as a larger successor.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Bell withdrew from the project in 1969 as it became clear it would not deliver a working system in the short term.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Shortly thereafter, GE decided to exit the computer industry entirely and sold the division to Honeywell in 1970.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Honeywell offered Multics commercially, but with limited success.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics has numerous features intended to ensure high availability so that it would support a computing utility similar to the telephone and electricity utilities.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Modular hardware structure and software architecture are used to achieve this.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The system can grow in size by simply adding more of the appropriate resource, be it computing power, main memory, or disk storage.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Separate access control lists on every file provide flexible information sharing, but complete privacy when needed.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics has a number of standard mechanisms to allow engineers to analyze the performance of the system, as well as a number of adaptive performance optimization mechanisms.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Due to its many novel and valuable ideas, Multics has had a significant influence on computer science despite its faults.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Its most lasting effect on the computer industry was to inspire the creation of Unix, which carried forward many Multics features, but was able to run on less expensive hardware.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Unix was developed at Bell to allow their Multics team to continue their research using smaller machines, first a PDP-7 and ultimately the PDP-11.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics implements a single-level store for data access, discarding the clear distinction between files (called *segments* in Multics) and *process memory*.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The memory of a process consists solely of segments that were mapped into its address space.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] To read or write to them, the process simply uses normal central processing unit (CPU) instructions, and the operating system takes care of making sure that all the modifications were saved to disk.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In POSIX terminology, it is as if every file were `mmap()`ed; however, in Multics there is no concept of *process memory*, separate from the memory used to hold mapped-in files, as Unix has.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] *All* memory in the system is part of *some* segment, which appears in the file system; this includes the temporary scratch memory of the process, its kernel stack, etc.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Segments are limited to 256 kilowords, just over 1 MB, because Multics hardware had 18-bit word addresses for the content of a segment.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Larger files are "multisegment files" and are handled differently.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The 256 kiloword limit was rarely encountered in practice, because at the time, one megabyte of memory was prohibitively expensive.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Another major new idea of Multics was dynamic linking, in which a running process can make external routines available by adding the segments containing them to its address space.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] This allows applications to always use the latest version of any external routine, since those routines are kept in other segments, which are dynamically linked only when a process first attempts to begin execution in them.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Since different processes can use different search rules, different users can end up using different versions of external routines.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Equally importantly, with the appropriate settings in the Multics security facilities, the code in the other segment can gain access to data structures maintained in a different process.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Dynamic linking in Multics does not require special dynamic-link libraries (DLLs); a program can dynamically link to any executable segment to which it has access rights.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Thus, to interact with an application running in part as a daemon (in another process), a user's process simply performs a normal procedure-call instruction to a code segment to which it had dynamically linked (a code segment that implemented some operation associated with the daemon).
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The code in that segment can then modify data maintained and used in the daemon.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] When the action necessary to commence the request is completed, a simple procedure return instruction returns control of the user's process to the user's code.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics also supports extremely aggressive on-line reconfiguration: central processing units, memory banks, disk drives, etc. can be added and removed while the system continues operating.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] System software development testing could be done on the second system, then the components of the second system were added back to the main user system, without ever having shut it down.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics is one of the earliest multiprocessor systems.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics is the first major operating system to be designed as a secure system from the outset.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Despite this, early versions of Multics were compromised repeatedly.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] This led to further work that made the system more secure, and prefigured modern security engineering techniques.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Break-ins became very rare once the second-generation hardware base was adopted; it has hardware support for ring-oriented security, a multilevel refinement of the concept of master mode.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] A US Air Force tiger team project tested Multics security in 1973 under the codeword ZARF.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] On 28 May 1997, the American National Security Agency declassified this use of the codeword ZARF.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics is the first operating system to provide a hierarchical file system, and file names can be of almost arbitrary length and syntax.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] A given file or directory can have multiple names (typically a long and short form), and symbolic links between directories are also supported.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics is the first to use the now-standard concept of per-process stacks in the kernel, with a separate stack for each security ring.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] It is also the first to have a command processor implemented as ordinary user code – an idea later used in the Unix shell.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] It is also one of the first written in a high-level language (Multics PL/I), after the Burroughs MCP system written in ESPOL, an expanded version of ALGOL.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The deployment of Multics into secure computing environments also spurred the development of innovative supporting applications.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 1975, Morrie Gasser of MITRE Corporation developed a pronounceable random word generator to address password requirements of installations such as the Air Force Data Services Center (AFDSC) processing classified information.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] To avoid guessable passwords, the AFDSC decided to assign passwords but concluded the manual assignment required too much administrative overhead.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Thus, a random word generator was researched and then developed in PL/I.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Instead of being based on phonemes or individual letters or clarities, the system employed phonemic segments (second order approximations of English) and other rules to enhance pronounceability and randomness, which was statistically modeled against other approaches.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] A descendant of this generator was added to Multics during Project Guardian.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 1964, Multics was developed initially for the GE-645 mainframe, a 36-bit system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] GE's computer business, including Multics, was taken over by Honeywell in 1970; around 1973, Multics was supported on the Honeywell 6180 machines, which included security improvements including hardware support for protection rings.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Bell Labs pulled out of the project in 1969 when it became clear that it would not produce a working system in the near future; some of the people who had worked on it there went on to create the Unix system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics development continued at MIT and General Electric.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] At MIT in 1975, use of Multics was declining, and it did not recover by 1976 to prior levels.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Finally by slashing prices, MIT managed to lure users back to Multics in 1978.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 1974 Honeywell entered into a development contract with the Air Force (with MIT as a sub-contractor) to develop a security kernel for Multics.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] This would involve reducing the size of the Multics hardcore by moving specific components of the supervisor out of Ring 0.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] One of the initial steps after carrying out a security evaluation was the implementation of a multilevel security framework within Multics called AIM (Access Isolation Mechanism).
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] This provided mandatory access control which could be enabled to supplement the already existing discretionary access control that Multics already possessed.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The resulting Project Guardian ran until termination in 1976; whilst most of its changes were not added to Multics, some parts of the project such as the proposed Secure Front End Processor was productized by Honeywell as SCOMP (Secure Communications Processor).
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 1985 the US Department of Defense awarded STOP 2.1 an A1 security classification.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The SCOMP and its STOP operating system eventually evolved via XTS-200 and XTS-300 into current XTS-400 offering of secure operating systems.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Honeywell continued system development until 1985.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] About 80 multimillion-dollar sites were installed, at universities, industry, and government sites.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The French university system had several installations in the early 1980s.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] After Honeywell stopped supporting Multics, users migrated to other systems, such as Unix.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Honeywell later slowly sold its Information Systems division (including rights to Multics) into a joint venture with Bull, and with NEC also participated, in 1986.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 1985, Multics was issued certification as a B2 level secure operating system using the Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria from the National Computer Security Center (NCSC), a division of the NSA; it was the first operating system evaluated to this level.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics was distributed from 1975 to 2000 by Groupe Bull in Europe, and by Bull HN Information Systems Inc.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] (the legal name of what formerly known as Honeywell Information Systems Inc. and Honeywell Bull Inc.) in the United States.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The last known Multics installation running natively on Honeywell hardware was shut down on October 30, 2000, at the Canadian Department of National Defence in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 2006 Bull HN released the source code for MR12.5, the final 1992 Multics release, to MIT.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Most of the system is now available as free software with the exception of some optional pieces such as TCP/IP.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In 2014, Multics was successfully run on current hardware using an emulator created by Multicians Harry Reed and Charles Anthony.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The 1.0 release of the emulator is available as of 2017.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] MR12.6f accompanies the 1.0 release of the emulator, and adds a few new features, including command line recall and editing using the video system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In August 2023, MR12.8 was released with various fixes and improvements.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The following is a list of programs and commands for common computing tasks that are supported by the Multics command-line interface.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The Multics shell language supports "active functions", which are similar to commands, but which return a string value.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] An active function is called by putting the active function name and the arguments to the active function in square brackets [ and ].
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The string returned by the active function is substituted into the command in place of the call to the active function.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] For example, when the command echo [working_dir] is processed, the active function working_dir is run; it returns the full path of the working directory, which is substituted into the command, so that the echo command prints the working directory.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Some programs can act either as commands or as active functions; when run as a command, its result is printed, and when run as an active function, its result is returned as a string.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Salus, author of a book covering Unix's early years, stated one position: "With Multics they tried to have a much more versatile and flexible operating system, and it failed miserably".
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] This position, however, is said to have been discredited in the computing community because many of Multics' technical innovations are used in modern commercial computing systems.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The permanently resident kernel of Multics, a system derided in its day as being too large and complex, was 135 KB of code.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The first MIT GE-645 had 512 kilowords of memory (2 MiB), a truly enormous amount at the time, and the kernel used a moderate portion of Multics main memory.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The entire system, including the operating system and the complex PL/I compiler, user commands, and subroutine libraries, consists of about 1500 source modules.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] These average roughly 200 lines of source code each, and compile to a total of roughly 4.5 MiB of procedure code, which was fairly large by the standards of the day.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Multics compilers generally optimise more for code density than CPU performance, for example using small sub-routines called *operators* for short standard code sequences, which makes comparison of object code size with modern systems less useful.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] High code density is a good optimisation choice for Multics as a multi-user system with expensive main memory.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] During its commercial product history, it was often commented internally that the Honeywell Information Systems (HIS) (later Honeywell-Bull) sales and marketing staff were more familiar with and comfortable making the business case for Honeywell's other computer line, the DPS 6 running GCOS 6.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The DPS-6 and GCOS 6 was a well-regarded and reliable platform for inventory, accounting, word processing, and vertical market applications, such as banking, where it had a sizeable customer base.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] In contrast, the full potential of Multics’ flexibility for even mundane tasks was not easy to comprehend in that era and its features were generally outside the skill set of contemporary business analysts.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The design and features of Multics influenced the Unix operating system, which was originally written by two Multics programmers, Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Influence of Multics on Unix is evident in many areas, including the hierarchical file system, redirection, the shell, and the naming of some commands.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] But the internal design philosophy is quite different, focusing on keeping the system small and simple, and so correcting some perceived deficiencies of Multics because of its high resource demands on the limited computer hardware of the time.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The name *Unix* (originally *Unics*) is itself a pun on *Multics*.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The *U* in Unix is rumored to stand for *uniplexed* as opposed to the *multiplexed* of Multics, further underscoring the designers' rejections of Multics' complexity in favor of a more straightforward and workable approach for smaller computers.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Ken Thompson, in a transcribed 2007 interview with Peter Seibel refers to Multics as "overdesigned and overbuilt and over everything.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] They [Massachusetts Institute of Technology] still claim it's a monstrous success, but it just clearly wasn't".
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] On the influence of Multics on Unix, Thompson stated that "the things that I liked enough (about Multics) to actually take were the hierarchical file system and the shell — a separate process that you can replace with some other process".
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Dennis Ritchie wrote that the design of Unix was influenced by MIT's CTSS, which was the immediate ancestor of Multics.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The Prime Computer operating system, PRIMOS, was referred to as "Multics in a shoebox" by William Poduska, a founder of the company.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Poduska later moved on to found Apollo Computer, whose AEGIS and later Domain/OS operating systems, sometimes called "Multics in a matchbox", extends the Multics design to a networked graphics workstation environment.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The Stratus VOS operating system of Stratus Computer (now Stratus Technologies) is very strongly influenced by Multics, and both its external user interface and internal structure bear many close resemblances to the older project.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The high-reliability, availability, and security features of Multics are extended in Stratus VOS to support a new line of fault tolerant computer systems supporting secure, reliable transaction processing.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] Stratus VOS is the most directly related descendant of Multics still in active development and production usage today.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] General Motors' Multiple Console Time Sharing System (MCTS) for the Control Data Corporation STAR-100 computer was based on Multics.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The protection architecture of Multics, restricting the ability of code at one level of the system to access resources at another, was adopted as the basis for the security features of ICL's VME operating system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] The Edinburgh Multiple Access System (EMAS) draws particularly on the one-level store concept used by Multics, providing access to files only by mapping them into memory.
[src:bcpl-b-language/multics] All memory space is associated with a segment.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] In computer programming, **self-hosting** is the use of a program as part of the toolchain or operating system that produces new versions of that same program—for example, a compiler that can compile its own source code.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Self-hosting software is commonplace on personal computers and larger systems.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Other programs that are typically self-hosting include kernels, assemblers, command-line interpreters and revision control software.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] An operating system is self-hosted when the toolchain to build the operating system runs on that same operating system.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] For example, Windows can be built on a computer running Windows.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Before a system can become self-hosted, another system is needed to develop it until it reaches a stage where self-hosting is possible.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] When developing for a new computer or operating system, a system to run the development software is needed, but development software used to write and build the operating system is also necessary.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] This is called a bootstrapping problem or, more generically, a chicken or the egg dilemma.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] A solution to this problem is the cross compiler (or cross assembler when working with assembly language).
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] A cross compiler allows source code on one platform to be compiled for a different machine or operating system, making it possible to create an operating system for a machine for which a self-hosting compiler does not yet exist.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Once written, software can be deployed to the target system using means such as an EPROM, floppy diskette, flash memory (such as a USB thumb drive), or JTAG device.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] This is similar to the method used to write software for gaming consoles or for handheld devices like cellular phones or tablets, which do not host their own development tools.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Once the system is mature enough to compile its own code, the cross-development dependency ends.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] At this point, an operating system is said to be self-hosted.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Software development using compiler or interpreters can also be self hosted when the compiler is capable of compiling itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Since self-hosted compilers suffer from the same bootstrap problems as operating systems, a compiler for a new programming language needs to be written in an existing language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] So the developer may use something like assembly language, C/C++, or even a scripting language like Python or Lua to build the first version of the compiler.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Once the language is mature enough, development of the compiler can shift to the compiler's native language, allowing the compiler to build itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Note that some of these points assume that the language runtime is also written in the same language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] The first self-hosting compiler (excluding assemblers) was written for Lisp by Hart and Levin at MIT in 1962.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] They wrote a Lisp compiler in Lisp, testing it inside an existing Lisp Interpreter.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] This technique is usually only practicable when an interpreter already exists for the very same language that is to be compiled; though possible, it is extremely uncommon to humanly compile a compiler with itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] The concept borrows directly from and is an example of the broader notion of running a program on itself as input, used also in various proofs in theoretical computer science, such as the proof that the halting problem is undecidable.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Ken Thompson started development on Unix in 1968 by writing and compiling programs on the GE-635 and carrying them over to the PDP-7 for testing.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] After the initial Unix kernel, a command interpreter, an editor, an assembler, and a few utilities were completed, the Unix operating system was self-hosting – programs could be written and tested on the PDP-7 itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Douglas McIlroy wrote TMG (a compiler-compiler) in TMG on a piece of paper and "decided to give his piece of paper to his piece of paper", doing the computation himself, thus compiling a TMG compiler into assembly, which he typed up and assembled on Ken Thompson's PDP-7.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Development of the GNU system relies largely on GCC (the GNU Compiler Collection) and GNU Emacs (a popular editor), making possible the self contained, maintained and sustained development of free software for the GNU Project.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] Many programming languages have self-hosted implementations: compilers that are both in and for the same language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/self-hosting-compilers] An approach is bootstrapping, where a core version of the language is initially implemented using another high-level language, assembler, or even machine language; the resulting compiler is then used to start building successive expanded versions of itself.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] A **system programming language** is a programming language used for system programming; such languages are designed for writing system software, which usually requires different development approaches when compared with application software.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Edsger Dijkstra referred to these languages as **machine oriented high order languages**, or **mohol**.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] General-purpose programming languages tend to focus on generic features to allow programs written in the language to use the same code on different computing platforms.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Examples of such languages include ALGOL and Pascal.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] This generic quality typically comes at the cost of denying direct access to the machine's internal workings, and this often has negative effects on performance.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] System languages, in contrast, are designed not for compatibility, but for performance and ease of access to the underlying computer hardware while still providing high-level programming concepts like structured programming.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Examples include Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL) and Systems Programming Language (SPL), both of which are ALGOL-like in syntax but tuned to their respective platforms.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Others are cross-platform software, but designed to work close to the hardware, like BLISS, JOVIAL, and BCPL.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Some languages straddle the system and application domains, bridging the gap between these uses.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] The canonical example is C, which is used widely for both system and application programming.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Some modern languages also do this such as Rust and Swift.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] In contrast with application languages, system programming languages typically offer more-direct access to the physical hardware of the machine: an archetypical system programming language in this sense was BCPL.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] System programming languages often lack built-in input/output (I/O) facilities because a system-software project usually develops its own I/O mechanisms or builds on basic monitor I/O or screen management facilities.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] The distinction between languages used for system programming and application programming became blurred over time with the widespread popularity of PL/I, C and Pascal.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] The earliest system software was written in assembly language mostly because no alternative existed, but also for reasons including efficiency of object code, compiling time, and ease of debugging.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Application languages such as FORTRAN were used for system programming, although they usually still required some routines to be written in assembly language.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Other languages in this category include MOL-360 and PL/S.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] As an example, a typical PL360 statement is `R9 := R8 and R7 shll 8 or R6`, signifying that registers 8 and 7 should be and'ed together, the result shifted left 8 bits, the result of that or'ed with the contents of register 6, and the final result placed into register 9.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] While PL360 is at the semantic level of assembly language, another kind of system programming language operates at a higher semantic level, but has specific extensions designed to make the language suitable for system programming.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] An early example of this kind of language is LRLTRAN, which extended Fortran with features for character and bit manipulation, pointers, and directly addressed jump tables.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Subsequently, languages such as C were developed, where the combination of features was sufficient to write system software, and a compiler could be developed that generated efficient object programs on modest hardware.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Such a language generally omits features that cannot be implemented efficiently, and adds a small number of machine-dependent features needed to access specific hardware abilities; inline assembly code, such as C's `asm` statement, is often used for this purpose.
[src:bcpl-b-language/system-programming-language] Although many such languages were developed, C and C++ are the ones which survived.
